poem:
The Quillivore

At dusk the flarefume shimmered bright,  
Through parchment hollows whispers flowed;  
It bled from ebon fonts of night,  
Where sizzleink and moonbeams glowed.  

“Beware the Quillivore,” they cried,  
“With thermo-fangs and scratch-claw spears!  
It slurps the ducts where inks reside,  
And suckles pens to ghostly tears.”  

Young Nibson seized his scrollblade keen;  
He heat-set ebonite feed so stark;  
He gauged the thermo-current scene,  
And pressed the tip to carbon mark.  

Past glyphflake drifts and twistling moors,  
He strode where simmer-vapors whined;  
The ceil of dusk unlatched its doors,  
And inkquake tremors trailed behind.  

Then from a blistered scroll-tree stump  
The looming Quillivore unfurled;  
“Skrish-skraw!” it hissed with guttered thump;  
Its talons skritched a ribbon-swirl.  

One stroke! the scrollblade flash-unwound;  
Snap-clack! the heat-set shield held fast;  
The thermo-lume sang, spark by sound,  
And quill and fang lay spent at last.  

Back through the twistling moors he sped,  
Past emberedd and glyphflake shore;  
The parchmice chirred, their terror shed,  
To write-wind hums forevermore.  

Once more the flarefume shimmered bright,  
Through parchment hollows calm repose;  
And quills at peace in gentle light,  
Where sizzleink in silence flows.

The Ballad of the Tyranotype

When leaden sorts lay loose and low,  
And galleys gleamed in inky tide,  
The clatterquills clink-clankied so;  
“Beware Tyranotype!” they cried.  

Stay clear its jaws of jagged brass,  
His beardly mentor gravely spoke;  
It snaps the fonts that typos pass,  
And leaves the margins black with smoke.  

He seized his trusty setting stick,  
A slugiron of tempered steel;  
He donned his proofsheet battle-quick,  
To bring Tyranotype to keel.  

Through gurry-galley glooms he strode,  
The nickled sorts went tikka-tak;  
When sudden—hush!—the furnace glowed,  
Forth slunk the beast with click-clack clack.  

Its pica-razors snapped and sprang;  
The hero lunged with lettered might;  
Skirr-skrack! slugiron sharply rang,  
And darkness shivered into light.  

He chased the cur through caseline maze;  
Then split its spine of churning lead;  
With hush-hroom! sparks consumed the haze,  
Tyranotype lay smelted dead.  

Back through the pressroom's rattling door,  
He bore the beast’s bent tympan shell;  
The mentor cheered, the galleys roared,  
“Now set the form, and set it well!”  

When leaden sorts lay loose and low,  
And galleys gleamed in inky tide,  
The clatterquills clink-clankied so;  
“Beware Tyranotype!” they cried.

Night-Blooming Cereus Vigil

Beneath the hush of quartz-lit skies  
The cereus kept secret bloom;  
While lantern-moths in driftlings rise,  
And shadowbells foretell its doom.  

“Beware the Bloomfang, thorn of night!”  
The elder mists in hush would croon;  
It glides on musk-soaked wings of flight,  
Shun, child, its perfumed pall at moon!  

I wound my vine-lace round my wrist,  
And drew the spine-bright sabrevine;  
I tasted dusk-distilling mist,  
And waited by the thornlit shrine.  

Whir-whush! the bloom-cloud burst in spray;  
The Bloomfang flashed its ember stare;  
It slither-spiraled through the spray,  
And hiss-brummed darkness into glare.  

I swung the sabrevine on high;  
Klin-clang! its thornplate cracked apart;  
Moonquartz flew shrieking from the sky,  
Steel-scented hush devoured its heart.  

The petals burst like silent drums,  
And soothed the air with moonlit ease;  
We drank their musk in blooming sums,  
Our breaths unknotted into ease.  

Once more the hush of quartz-lit skies  
Enfolds the flower, free from doom;  
Moonmirth and vinewind softly rise,  
And silence guards its midnight bloom.

Spaghettisaur in Patchland

Gloam wires hummed in the crosspatch coil;  
Sockets of spectra tone;  
Curlicue cables looped in coil;  
In syncopated tone.  

Beware the dire Spaghettisaur,  
Its cables clench and feast;  
Its hiss rings harsh, Spaghettisaur!  
Shun its chromatic feast.  

He gripped his gleamloop osciblade;  
A ringmod shield to roar;  
With sync-stab stance he raised the blade;  
Against that thrumming roar.  

And while the actidials tick;  
Wet wirings wound in hum;  
The Spaghettisaur slid—slick tick;  
Its maw a midi hum.  

Bzzrrt—zap! the osciblade flashed fast;  
Whoom-whirr! the chorus roared;  
He cleft the writhing patch-heap fast;  
Clak! and the buses roared.  

He lugged the severed jacks back home;  
His mentor hummed anew;  
“O patchling brave, the rig is home!”  
Let modules sing anew.  

Gloam wires hummed in the crosspatch coil;  
Sockets of spectra tone;  
Curlicue cables looped in coil;  
In syncopated tone.

Wowflap and Flutterclank

Soft hissing filled the spoolish dusk,  
The tapelets twined in ferro light;  
Through wowflap winds and flutter musk  
They warbled wan beneath the night.  

“Beware the Clatterpuff!” they cried.  
“The wowfangs pierce, the pitch will swim!  
Bewatch the Warblegator glide,  
Shun fluttermoan and drop-out dim!”  

I wound my chromestripe blade with care;  
I clasped a bias-shield of felt;  
I sought the Whirrophone’s dark lair;  
My heart beat sync to meters dealt.  

Thrum-thrum went spores of ribbon air,  
Ka-chunk! the Clatterpuff burst near;  
Its warblejaw hummed out despair;  
Wa-woo it howled upon my ear.  

I flipped the heads, reversed the hum;  
My chromestripe blade sang ferro bright;  
I spliced its hiss with counter-drum;  
The beast unspooled into the night.  

O chimeful hush! the deck was still;  
The tapelets danced in steady line;  
No flutterghost could bend their will;  
The wow was tamed to true design.  

Soft hissing warms the spoolish dusk,  
The tapelets twine in ferro light;  
Through calm-bound winds and gentle musk,  
They sing in pitch, forever right.

Opalescent Wyrm

Ere moonspill glazed the rift-glade bright,
While prismic vapors shimmer-swayed;
The opal play-of-color light
Around the path where dreamlings strayed.

“Beware the Opalescent Wyrm;
Its prism-fangs ignite the lake;
Beware its spectrum-seeking term,
That makes the noon-stones snap and quake.”

The youngling gripped his crysta-blade;
He donned a gleamshard carapace;
He traced the echo-mines and prayed
For opal gods to guard his chase.

Skreel-splack! the scarlet fissures yawned,
Out lunged the shimmer-sliding Scroath;
Its iris-plasma frills were dawned,
And chroma-fire hissed down its throat.

Quick-stanced, he flung the crysta-blade;
Whirr-thrumm it hummed through spectral air;
It clove the beast in prism-shade,
Till flare-cores burst in blinded glare.

He bore the shattered rainbow-scale
Home over hushling opal sand;
The elders sang the chroma-tale,
And set the peace-torch in his hand.

Ere moonspill glazed the rift-glade bright,
And prismic vapors shimmer-swayed;
No opal play-of-color fright
But gentle dreams along the shade.

The Lissabloom

Soft phaselight swept the flicker hall  
While coax coils hummed a loomy low;  
Through lissajous the spectres crawl,  
Oscilloscopes in glow.  

Beware the Lissabloom, my child!  
The squealing waves it wraps and warps;  
Beware the Spattergraph so wild,  
And all its twisty sharps!  

He gripped his phase-edge neon blade;  
Long time the jitter grief he chased;  
Then paused, his heartbeat retro-stayed,  
Sync-steady, nerves emplaced.  

Beside the nodal Whisper-tree,  
He tuned the hush to zero beat;  
And while he watched the trembling spree,  
Hwooo-patter padded feet.  

Schwizz! A-leap the Lissabloom rose,  
Its ribbon jaws went phase-to-phase;  
It looped a snarling lissajous,  
Whir-whang in neon haze!  

Zip-zap! Through vector space he swung;  
Ker-clang! the echo sliced the gloom;  
The creature crashed in static tongues,  
Dead-spread, a silent bloom.  

Re-home he strode with quantum grin;  
His elder beamed with signal pride;  
Pulse-plausive cheers unspooled within,  
Hip-hip oscillo-wide!  

Soft phaselight swept the flicker hall  
While coax coils hummed a loomy low;  
Through lissajous the spectres crawl,  
Oscilloscopes in glow.

Shuttlewite and the Loomlit Gloam

In loomlit gloam the shuttles pick,  
And snurling yarnwinds twist and chime;  
Soft whirr-ka-clack, the heddles click,  
O warpweave hush of wefting time.  

Beware the Shuttlewite, my child;  
The crankled fang, the netting glare;  
Beware the clove-ed bobbin wild,  
The pucker-snap of tangling snare.  

He took his trimblade in his hand;  
Long pause he spun before the fight;  
And by the creelroot he would stand,  
To steady threads and test their bite.  

Deep through the carding dusk he strode;  
Gling-glong the pinions hummed ahead;  
All threadlings fled across the road,  
While Shuttlewite through shadow sped.  

Zip-zang! the creature lunged and snarled;  
The trimblade flashed in woven arc;  
One cleaving swipe—the heddles jarred;  
Ker-chud! fell mute the Shuttlewark.  

He mended breath, unwarped his brow;  
He bundled up the fraying dread;  
Then homeward through the hedded slough,  
With spindle-pride to hearth and bed.  

O clack the beams! rejoice the loom!  
His nana crowed a weaver's cheer;  
“Thou snipped the beast of shuttle-gloom,  
Come taste the twist of vict'ry here.”  

In loomlit gloam the shuttles pick;  
No snurling menace skews the seam;  
Soft whirr-ka-clack, the heddles tick,  
And peace is woven through the dream.

The Marmorgoyle and the Pietra-Dura Dawn

At pietra-dura dawn by bay  
The glimmersheen of agate gleam,  
While marblestitch and jasper play,  
Bright hush across the onyx stream.  

“Bewarn,” my master murmured low,  
“The Marmorgoyle with gritstone grin;  
Its chiselwhirl can chip your glow;  
No shield of gem can guard your skin.”  

I forged a flareflake staff of light,  
And donned a stone-mask hard and true;  
I mapped the caves in chromagraph,  
Where lumicore in silence grew.  

Through selenite and shale I strode,  
The echoes hissed “krissh-krissh” again;  
Gemmifret winds around me flowed,  
As duskstone dust my footsteps drew.  

Then—THRUM!—the veins of marble split;  
Out poured the looming Marmorgoyle,  
With grout-thick wings that boom and flit,  
Its eyes two pits of swirling oil.  

We circled under vault of ore;  
I raised the flareflake staff ablaze;  
CLANG! struck the chiselbeast once more,  
And cleft its grout-bound heart in rays.  

The Marmorgoyle fell, mute as slab;  
Stone burst as bright mosaic dew;  
I heaved the shards into my cab,  
And traced the moonlit path I knew.  

At pietra-dura dawn by bay,  
Fresh panels bloom in onyx frame;  
Their marblestitch and jasper play,  
So mem’ry hums the agate flame.

The Targrumble

At railbend dusk the sleepers steam,  
With crosstie creosote perfume,  
The signal lamps ignite and gleam,  
Through grovelight pooled beside the flume.  

Beware the Targrumble, my child!  
The rail-worm rife with soot and glare;  
Its creaking jaws clap loud and wild,  
And bolt-sparks fizz within its lair.  

He took his bright bullspike in hand,  
He donned a helm of lantern-brass;  
Long hours he mapped the iron land  
Where cinder-mists like phantoms pass.  

By grindstone moon he strode the ties;  
Winds in chalkfleck sang whistle-roo;  
Plank-clack, plank-clack, the track replies,  
Skycrowds of soot obscured the view.  

And as he knelt by switchrod bend,  
The Targrumble uncoiled in smoke;  
Skrelch! went its jaws, a railwrought rend,  
Hot ballast spat with fiery stroke.  

One step, one swing, the bullspike rose;  
It sang through tar with ringing dread;  
Whunk! till the tempered point was red;  
Targrumble toppled; off it ran.  

He wiped the spike on ember grass;  
Back down the grade he paced with cheer;  
No Targrumble lurked in the pass,  
The wind hauled freight of sweet frontier.  

At railbend dusk the sleepers steam;  
The crosstie creosote drifts bloom;  
Lamp-gleam again, no shadows scheme,  
Safe grovelight beside the flume now.

Inkbit and the Snick-Saw

At brayer-time the rollers sang  
Across the lino's inky glade;  
The chipsy shreds went scritch-a-clang,  
And printlings flicked within the shade.  

Beware the gummy Inkbit beast;  
Its press-pad grin can smudge a scroll;  
With wuffle-whump it leaps, released,  
And leave no smirkish markless droll.  

He gripped his carven Snick-saw blade;  
And tied his plume-stitched proofing vest;  
Through inkish fog he forward strayed;  
Click-clack, click-clack, all rollers pressed.  

The lino-field lay slick and black;  
Each brayer bowed a rubber tune;  
But hushed became the click-a-clack  
While shadows scratched a gummy rune.  

Ho! From the gurgle-gutter sprang  
The Inkbit, squelched on rubber claws;  
It thrumble-thunked—ker-splash!—ker-clang,  
And skirled its drooling inky jaws.  

One sweep! The Snick-saw sliced the muck;  
Ka-chik-ka-choom! the goo flew wide;  
He jab-ker-jabbed with plucky luck,  
Till Inkbit gulped its pride and died.  

Back through the press-lands home he strode;  
His apron streaked but spirit proud;  
The brayers burst in clatter-ode,  
Ker-skip! the lino laughed aloud.  

At brayer-time the rollers sing;  
Their rubber hymns on troughs unfold;  
The chipsy shreds still scritch-a-ring,  
And tales of Inkbit fade untold.

Quarter-Sawn Shimmer

It was the quarter-sawning time,  
The grain-glow shimmered like a tide;  
Flimmergrain chimed in oaken chime,  
As sap-sounds sough along the side.  

Beware the Shimmermaw, my child!  
The plinth-back beast of rasping tone;  
With splinterfangs and finish wild,  
It shrieks kerr-CLACK through heart and bone.  

Take up the varnish-whetted blade;  
Hold fast the brace of beading glue;  
Steady your pulse in amber shade,  
And let the grain-guides carry you.  

He strode through curl and quavered stave;  
Luthier-leafs sang strum by strum;  
But in the sap a groaning wave  
Announced the beast with booming drum.  

Swick-SWOOP! it lunged, its lacquer jaws;  
The blade rang back in sparking flare;  
He checked the sweep, no stutter-pause,  
And sliced the shimmer clean to air.  

Down fell the beast in shatter-dust;  
Its grain-ghost leaked in ribbon smoke;  
He bound the shards with patient trust,  
And sealed the knots with finish-oak.  

He paced back through the sounding grain;  
Luthier-leafs breathed hush and glow;  
His heart beat clean of fear and strain,  
For Shimmermaw lies laid below.  

It is the quarter-sawning time;  
The grain-glow hums, serene and wide;  
No shadow mars the oaken chime,  
While sap-lights murmur like a tide.

The Seamraak and the Boro Patch

When stitchful dusk draped rafu threads  
They swirled and sashayed through the weft;  
Quilt-spirits twirled among the shreds,  
While patchling boro hummed and left.  

Beware the Seamraak, needle-gnarled!  
The wise old Darnor softly said;  
His thimble-teeth leave fabric scarred;  
His clik-a-clak unspools the thread!  

He took his needle-saber keen,  
A belt of patches round his waist;  
He stitched charm of indigo sheen,  
And vowed he would not seam in haste.  

Through tatami groves he trod late,  
The moon unrolled a silver skein;  
His heart beat time with wary gait,  
Tikka-tak echoed in the plain.  

The Seamraak burst from selvedge dark,  
Its button-eyes flashed crimson mark;  
He crackled “Krriik!”—a lightning spark,  
And swooped like shears on cotton lark.  

Up sprang the youth with needle-blade;  
He parried zip and zapping sweep;  
Then thrust along the bias grade,  
“Shku-shrak!”—the Seamraak sank to sleep.  

He bundled up the fallen shreds,  
Restitched the gaps with patient art;  
And set them back as humble threads,  
Warm peace re-seamed the waiting heart.  

When stitchful dawn lifts rafu threads,  
They glide, relumed, across the weft;  
No Seamraak prowls these mended shreds,  
While patchling boro hums bereft.

Fishtail Sweep and the Clamptrout

The dusk was dreep and murklesway,  
Where fleekling reeds went swup at dark;  
I watched the fishtail gouge at play,  
Scooping a whorl through ember-dark.  

“Beware the Clamptrout!” Father said,  
“Its flimmer-fins in midnight loom;  
With clackle-bite it snaps the head  
And drags the splintered hull to gloom.”  

I hefted up my whittle-steel,  
The fishtail gouge along its groove;  
I bound it to my faith of steel,  
And let the moonlit shavings groove.  

Through plinker bogs I tramped,—ker-snap!  
The snudder fog began to coil;  
My heartstrings hummed a tension snap,  
While stitchlings wriggled in the coil.  

SKRANG! It sundered the silver veil;  
The Clamptrout thrashed with jagged scale;  
I felt the water crack its veil,  
As rozzle teeth clinked fang on scale.  

I flicked the gouge in spiral slice;  
The flimmer fins recoiled in rush;  
KA-CHOCK! I carved a deeper slice,  
It sank beneath the bubble-rush.  

I lugged the limp-thing through the foam;  
The marshlights chimed in bubble-glee;  
Its jagged fins lay still in foam;  
My gouge hummed low with quiet glee.  

The dusk is dreep yet murklesway;  
The drained lagoon lies ember-dark;  
My fishtail gouge guides chips to sway,  
And dreams resettle in the bark.

Clatterclocky

Beware the Clatterclock, my child;  
Its tickers hiss through foggy code.  
In buzzing burble, keys beguiled  
May lure you off the buzzing road.  

He grasped his brassbound transmi-sword,  
The dit-dat shield of tempered tone;  
With steely nerve he set the chord,  
And faced the clicksome crypt alone.  

Tap-TAP! Tap-TAP! the tunnel spoke;  
Ker-CLACKs cascaded left and right;  
From clangled shade a shadow broke,  
Its eyes two pulsing pins of night.  

The Clatterclock, in jerking gin,  
Unspooled its screechy springling jaw;  
It thrumble-threshed the copper din  
And hacked the air with hammer caw.  

One dash, two dots—he keyed the flare;  
The sparkline smote its rattling breast;  
With blizzled squeal and fizzled glare,  
The beast unsprung and clanked to rest.  

He strode back through the signal breeze;  
The night no longer hissed with ticks;  
The smiling wiremen raised their keys,  
And chimed a clinking clattermix.  

So rest, yet heed the clicking night;  
Beware the Clatterclock once more;  
For codes can conjure stealthy fright,  
Tap-TAP! Tap-TAP! across the floor.

Balogne of the Krenovian Throat

Through fizzle-fog the twilight groaned,  
The krenovian plane throat held;  
Take heed, else steelwing night be stoned,  
By Balogne’s rasp of rust unquelled.  

He oiled his whickering slice-gear,  
He strapped the flinder-cloak about;  
He murmured runes to stiffen fear,  
While tick-tock anvils chimed without.  

The gloombirds barfed their tarnished song;  
Split-skyward, silver rivets rang.  
Yet through the din, and all along,  
Came “Wraff-ka-ROON!”, the Balogne’s clang.  

Then sprung the beast with spiral snout,  
Its corkscrew throat belched ozone flame;  
His slice-gear hummed; he leapt about,  
To meet the shrike-scaled Balogne’s claim.  

“KRAK-ka-CHONK!”—steel kisses bone hard;  
He cleaved the whirl-jaw right to core.  
One second’s hush, then rupture-groan;  
The Balogne shrieked, and shrieked no more.  

He bagged the cog-flecked trophy head,  
And turned toward candle-chimney shore;  
The gloombirds hushed; the fog lay dead,  
While brassbell dawn began to pour.  

His kin in clatter-hall made cheer;  
They crowned him with a zindle ring;  
And though they cheered, they harbored fear,  
For darker depths hide every thing.  

Through fizzle-fog the twilight groaned,  
The krenovian plane throat slept;  
And somewhere, far beyond the zoned,  
New Balognes coil, their razors kept.

The Clatterwurm and the Tin-Top Rain

Rain rasped upon the tin-top shed,  
And bugle-gusts went ping-pa-pong;  
The gutter-gnarls in slumber fled,  
While dribbledark hummed puddle-song.  

Now Granny Grit her finger shook,  
“Beware the Clatterwurm,” she warned;  
“His clap-claw tail and thunder look  
Will boom your bones till bolts are scorned!”  

I snatched my trusty Rattleblade,  
A corruspear of copper lean;  
Through pitter-paths of drench and shade  
I stalked the rattling rain-ravine.  

Plunk-plank! the plates above me rang;  
The Clatterwurm came clanging nigh;  
His hammer-head hurra-boom-bang,  
Lit lightning-lurid in the sky.  

We circled through the splatterglow;  
He clanged, and iron echoes sung;  
My Rattleblade hiss-whistled low,  
And cleft his cannon-maw unsung.  

I lugged the silent shell back home;  
The gutters gurgled lull-a-lay;  
Granny hailed my splintered bright chrome,  
And smiled the stormy fears away.  

Rain rasped upon the tin-top shed,  
Its ping-pa-pong a gentle proof;  
For Clatterwurm is clatter-dead,  
And calmness crowns the silver roof.
